{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17504237","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17504237"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T11:13:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2309"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2309"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.07,0.16,0.01,0.75]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101925"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2309","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2309"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2309"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84382"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1009"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"687"},{"type":"contributions","id":"701"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1163"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101925","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101925"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 88-year-old woman is brought by her son to her GP clinic as she has increasing difficulty managing at home. This occurs in the setting of her 90-year-old husband being readmitted to hospital following an acute exacerbation of his chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) on a background of several inpatient admissions over the past nine months.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe couple have lived together for the past 60 years in a self-described happy marriage. She still enjoys her daily hobbies such as knitting and states that she is happy her loved ones visit her often. However, there are moments where she has trouble recalling the names of her friends that visit her.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn further questioning, her son points out that his mother has been skipping meals more frequently and has started neglecting her personal hygiene. She often forgets to take her regular statin for hypercholesterolaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn clinical examination, she is alert and oriented to person but not date and time. She is observed to mobilise independently. A MMSE is performed which shows a score of 19/30 from a previous score of 24/30 half a year ago. No further significant examination findings are identified.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of her presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Delirium","Normal grief","Depression","Anxiety","Dementia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInability to manage at home is often misinterpreted in the geriatric population. A diagnosis of \u003Cstrong\u003Edementia\u003C/strong\u003E is most likely given the history of impaired performance in personal activities of daily living as suggested by her neglect in personal hygiene, forgetfulness with her medication regimen and often skipping meals. The manifestation of her concerns could suggest that her husband may have managed her day to day tasks but unfortunately his illness has limited his capacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDelirium should always be considered in acute settings. However, there is no suggestion of acute fluctuations in attention and altered consciousness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt is unusual for grief to manifest in this setting whilst she may be upset over her husband\u2019s frequent hospitalisation. It is unlikely that she is depressed since there is no indication of changes in her mood. Severe depression can manifest as self-neglect although this setting is more indicative of forgetfulness rather than loss of interest. However, it is always important to consider that she might be worried about her husband\u2019s well-being and prognosis - Depression could develop in time if her concerns are not properly addressed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThere is no evidence that she is experiencing anxiety.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dementia is often insidious in onset and as a diagnosis, can easily be overlooked."],"references":["Geldmacher DS, Whitehouse PJ. Evaluation of dementia. N Engl J Med 1996; 335:330.","Petersen RC, Stevens JC, Ganguli M, et al. Practice parameter: early detection of dementia: mild cognitive impairment (an evidence-based review). Report of the Quality Standards Subcommittee of the American Academy of Neurology. Neurology 2001; 56:1133."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84382"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2309"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84382","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84382"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-05T15:31:57+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T15:31:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2309"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101925"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,